5. Summary Table – Node, SHA, AES, and Brain
Component Role Relation to Brain
Body node Silicone encapsulated sensor; computes SHA‑256 and AES‑256‑GCM Completely external – no direct neural connection
SHA‑256 Generates fingerprint of biological state; ensures data integrity Not computed by neurons; done by microprocessor
AES‑256‑GCM Encrypts data at rest and in transit; protects privacy Not involved; hardware crypto engine
RF mesh Exchanges encrypted packets between nodes Uses radio waves, not synaptic transmission
Computer hub Displays network topology; runs higher‑level algorithms Visualisation for Chase; no link to his brain
The number of “neuro connections” that form a node is zero – the node is an electronic device. The analogy (node ≈ 1,000 neurons) is only a computational equivalence for specific tasks, not a biological statement. The true connection between the brain and the node network is through EEG sensing (reading) and RF stimulation (writing) – both are wireless and non‑invasive
